 <problem newNameSpace>
  <setup>
    <selectFromSequence name="a" from="2" to="10"/>
    <select name="b">
      <option selectWeight="1"><math>0</math></option>
      <option selectWeight="1"><math>1</math></option>
      <option selectWeight="2"><math>2</math></option>
      <option selectWeight="2"><math>3</math></option>
      <option selectWeight="1"><math>4</math></option>
    </select>
    <math name="c">$a^$b</math>
    <!--maths for incorrect answers-->
  </setup>
  
  
  <!--testing-->
  <!-- <p>a = $a</p>
  <p>b = $b</p>
  <p>c = $c</p> -->
  <!--testing-->
  
  
  <p><m>y = \log_{$a} $c{simplify}</m></p> 
  
  <p><m>y = </m> 
    <answer name="ans1">
      <mathInput name="userAns"/>
      <award name="correct" symbolicEquality>
        <when>$userAns = $b</when>
      </award>
  
      <award name="multiplied" credit="0">
        <when>$userAns = $a$c</when>
      </award>
    </answer>
  </p>
  
  
  <!--*********************************************
              Feedbacks
  **********************************************-->
  <setup>
    <select name="correctFeedback" type="text">
      <option>Awesome!</option>
      <option>Great job!</option>
      <option>Fantastic!</option>
      <option>Nice work!</option>
      <option>Amazing!</option>
      <option>Excellent!</option>
      <option>Right on!</option>
      <option>Perfect!</option>
    </select>
  </setup>
    <feedback condition="$correct">$correctFeedback</feedback>
    <feedback condition="$multiplied">The logarithm function returns the exponent that the base must be <em>raised to</em> that results in the input argument, <m>$c{simplify}</m>. It looks like you took the product of <m>$a</m> and <m>$c{simplify}</m>, which is not the correct operation.</feedback>
    <feedback condition="$c = 1 and $ans1.creditAchieved != 1 and $ans1.responseHasBeenSubmitted">It's a good time to review your properties of logarithms.
  <p>Recall, that any number raised to the <m>0^{th}</m> power is equal to <m>1</m>, so for any <m>a</m>, 
      <me>a^0 = 1.</me></p>
      <p>Now, applying this fact to the logarithm function, we have that the logarithm function, evaluated at <m>1</m> for any base <m>a</m> must be equal to <m>0</m>,
        <me>\log_a 1 = 0 \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^0 = 1</me></p>
    </feedback>
  
      <feedback condition="$ans1.numSubmissions > 2 and $ans1.creditAchieved != 1">
        <p>The definition of the logarithm function is:
    <me>\log_a x = y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^y = x</me>
  where <m>a >0, a \neq 1</m> and <m> x > 0</m>. The first step when computing the logarithm without a calculator is to rewrite the equation in exponential form. Then, ask yourself, "what exponent must <m>a</m> be <em>raised to</em> to result in <m>x</m>?" The answer to this question is the exponent <m>y</m>.</p>
      </feedback>
    
  
  
  
  <!--*********************************************
              Hint
  **********************************************-->
  
    
  
  <!--*********************************************
              Solution
  **********************************************-->
  <solution>
  <ul>
    <li>Rewrite the logarithmic expression as an exponential:
    <md>
        <mrow>\log_a x \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;a^y = x \amp\text{general definition}</mrow>
        <mrow>\log_{$a} $c{simplify} \amp= y \;\;\text{implies}\;\;$a^y = $c{simplify} \amp\text{rewrite given logarithm as an exponential}</mrow>
        <mrow>\log_{$a} $c{simplify} \amp= $b \;\;\amp y \;\text{must be equal to}\;\;$b\;\;\text{for the equation to be true}</mrow>
      </md></li>
  </ul>
      
  </solution>
  </problem>
  
  
  
